communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[The Greek Island Lesvos is close to the Turkish mainland, from where, most
probably, infected vectors (or, though less likely, infected ruminants)
have been introduced. Information on the breed of the affected sheep would
be helpful. The virus may have been circulating for some time in the
region, particularly in Turkey, without being noticed. In the absence of a
considerable serological surveillance, the discovery of BTV activity
depends upon the emergence of observable clinical signs. Such changes/signs
are expected mainly in sheep of susceptible breeds (e.g. Chios dairy sheep).

In contrast with northern, cooler parts of Europe, where _Culicoides_
activity is anticipated to have already peaked, in the eastern
Mediterranean the vectors may still reach their peak activity during
November. Hence, further spread of the virus can not be excluded.

The serotyping of the BTV strain(s) involved are awaited with interest. -
Mod.AS]
